antic_type\": \"\",\n        \"description\": \"\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"column\": \"model_response\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"dtype\": \"string\",\n        \"num_unique_values\": 100,\n        \"samples\": [\n          \"Dystrophic Epidermolysis Bullosa (DEB) is a group of rare genetic skin disorders characterized by fragile skin that blisters and wounds easily, even from minor injury or friction. This condition is caused by mutations in the COL7A1 gene, which provides instructions for making type VII collagen.\\n\\nType VII collagen is a key component of anchoring fibrils, which are responsible for attaching the epidermis (outer layer of the skin) to the dermis (inner layer of the skin). In DEB, the mutations in the COL7A1 gene result in the production of abnormal type VII collagen or a complete lack of it, leading to the blistering and wounding of the skin.\\n\\nThere are two main types of DEB:\\n\\n1. Dystrophic Epidermolysis Bullosa, Generalized Junctional (DEB-GJ): This type is characterized by blistering that occurs at the dermal-epidermal junction. Affected individuals may also have nail dystrophy, scarring, and joint contractures.\\n\\n2. Dystrophic Epidermolysis Bullosa, Stratified Junctional (DEB-SJ): This type is less common and is characterized by blistering that occurs within the epidermis. Affected individuals may have nail dystrophy, scarring, and dental problems.\\n\\nIt's important to note that DEB can vary greatly in severity, even within the same family. Some individuals may have mild symptoms, while others may have more severe symptoms that require extensive medical care.\\n\\nIf you suspect that you or someone you know may have DEB, it's crucial to consult a healthcare professional for a proper diagnosis and treatment plan. Genetic testing can confirm the diagnosis and help determine the specific type of DEB.\"\n        ],\n        \"semantic_type\": \"\",\n        \"description\": \"\"\n      }\n    }\n  ]\n}",
